Bakal tenant: The stoves are warming, he signed a higher rent.
An imposing elderly man came out of the door of the customer center of the company RPG Byty of the "coal baron" Zdenek Bakal, the largest private owner of apartments for rent in the Czech Republic.
He was carrying under his arm a file with three new leases for three apartments: his, his daughter and his son who is serving a sentence.
The deregulation has increased the rent to these three people.
Instead of paying 3500 the son will have to pay from next year for a 2+1 second category apartment 4100 crowns.
"And there is no hot water and the heating works on solid fuel," the man with the signature power pointed to his son's new contract.
"But I signed anyway," he said, angry and half resigned.
The citizen association of apartments BytyOKD.cz who described the new rental conditions as "immoral and indecent", advises tenants not to sign and wait until December 7, when a notice will be published to explain the method to use to claim.
But the man reacts to this with a gesture of his hand.
"One says that, the other says something else" frowning.
The Ostrava region becomes the laboratory of deregulation.
After New Year's Eve, this is what most apartments in the Czech Republic are waiting for, whose rents do not match the market price.
For this reason, Aktualne.cz decided to personally visit the "laboratory".
The RPG waiting room on Havirovska Street is one of four in the Ostrava region and it is already full on Tuesday at 9 a.m.
Right next to the door stands a security company guard with a device to call customers.
A special button, "rent 2011", is lit on the touch screen.
Only one press and one paper with a number comes out of the device.
You don't have time to read your "157" number as your number already starts lighting up on the big screen under the top of the waiting room.
In a fraction of a second, it's your turn.
After a short moment, an old couple arrives to inquire about the rent, but the new rents do not seem to concern the people in the waiting room.
The majority of people have come to solve common problems as everywhere - requests for repairs, insurance events and so on.
In the Ostrava area, people from more than 44,000 RPG apartments have been receiving mail with the new leases in their mailbox since around mid-November.
RPG Byty offers rent increases from 15 percent to 38 percent.
The special desk for new rents has been open to the public since November 18.
"It's been working for nearly a week, so it's still trying," replies the employee behind the counter after a moment of hesitation when the client presents himself as a journalist.
Deragulation and the former Bakal miners’ apartments are a very sensitive local subject.
The Vice-President of the parliament and from the Ostrava region Lubomir Zaoralek of the Social Democrats reported this quite sustainedly before the elections and it now fills the local newspapers.
“Twenty years after them, I want a new floor.”
"They didn't even change me a put...n board in the toilets, relieves in the introduction the mentioned man.
However, it is mostly, according to employees, retirees who come to make sure they will receive a discount on the new rent price if they sign now as promised RPG in a special offer.
This is a rebate of half the amount of rent that will be received by other tenants who have signed their new contract before December 15.
But the "deregulation" counter on Havirovaska Street is really not overwhelmed by questions.
“Among the 360 customers who came yesterday, only 40 to 50 came for rent,” the employee said.
And yet RPG presents on its website as well as in the windows of individual interviews on rents when necessary.
If the two sides do not agree on the rent, it is an independent court that will make the decision.
"It's not about threats, it's just about informing us about the unique and legitimate way to act legally," RPG said on its website.
"Here no one will go to court," thinks one of the RPG Byty employees and the man in the street in front of the customer center gives him his right.
“I have 13,000 retirement crowns and I have 5,000 crowns left to eat, I don’t have enough to go to court,” he said.
The employee suddenly feels uncomfortable.
"We'll see."
“Mr. Zaoralek in the media asks that no one sign and so people wait,” she says.
The regulation of rents ends in the Czech Republic with the beginning of 2011 and increases, according to RPG Byty, are an economic necessity.
"And, in addition, current rents still do not reach the level necessary for the simple maintenance of the fund for housing," recalls Pavel Klimes, director of the residential portfolio of the company RPG Byty, that it is precisely the negligence of the fund for housing that makes the tenant angry is the main reason for the increase in rent.
However, in 5 years between 2005 and 2010 RPG was able to invest with rents in apartments 4 billion, in four years from 2011 to 2014 this should be 5.2 billion.
The large screen hanging from the ceiling in front of the upholstered armchairs in the waiting room on Havirosvka Street, however, repeats some information indicated in red.
The rent increase in 2011 is 15 percent and concerns no less than 31,200 apartments, which is more than 90 percent of RPG apartments.
"And it will always be at most 7.50 Czech crowns per m2 per month," the screen says.
The 38 percent increase concerns only 400 apartments in the RPG portfolio.
"In these cases, this is an increase of a really low sum of 19.66 Czech crowns per m2," adds RPG.
Next year the rent will remain the same for 2,600 apartments.
RPG Byty promises that deregulation will not cause a radical but progressive increase over 4 to 8 years.
It adds other commitments: all the money from the increase in rents (see the graph) is returned to the apartments in the form of heating savings - new windows and heating.
Those who sign the agreement on the rent increase have priority.
The nursery school is also part of the offices included the architects.
the administrative building Avriopoint in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch. Design.
No one could have expected that it would also house a mini kindergarten with everything needed - colored walls, imaginative furniture, toys and finally a miniature playground on the terrace.
Since October of last year, the children of the employees of Arch. design can visit.
Architectural project company Arch. Design. whose workshops have produced a large number of constructions in Brno, has imagined its business mini-primary school since the first drafts of the Avriopoint building.
It employs about 90 people, mostly of the age to make children and it was important for women architects and project managers to be able to quickly return to work.
At the same time as reduced time employment contracts, the nursery school is a bonus offered to its employees by the company Arch. Design. as part of its social program.
Constructors and architects thus have the opportunity to combine work taking care of children.
It was the employees of Arch.Design themselves who imagined this kindergarten and with the support of the management they were able to obtain an endowment from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The mini-primary school is funded by the European Social Fund through the Operational Programme of Human Resources and the State Budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to the funding grants (up to 2.8 million CZK), they were able to buy equipment and equipment and after two years to ensure qualified personnel as well as the start-up.
After the use of the funding endowment (two years) the company Arch. Design. has the obligation after 3 years to operate the mini-primary school on its own funds.
The preparation of the project lasted a year and it was the company Economy rating that helped to apply for the endowment.
Childcare is provided by qualified staff, a nurse and a kindergarten teacher take care of the children throughout the day. Children can go to kindergarten without age limitation but they are over threeyears oldfor the most part.
As it is a "mini kindergarten" there can only be 5 children present at the same time, but during the day there are more that replace each other.
The operation of the school is flexible according to the needs of the parents and the children of all employees have the same right to use this school without looking at the hierarchical position.
Although the program involves individual care and education, the mini-primary school curriculum is comparable to that for preschool education.
Children do not only play but quality education is also guaranteed - from the beginning to the preparation for school benches we teach English.
The class is equipped not only with imaginative toys and games but also with a computer that children can use.
The presence of small children in society creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can at any time control their child and not have the stress of a delay to pick up the children from a school away from the parent’s workplace.
Parents therefore use their working time in the most productive way.
It is no wonder that a natural relationship of loyalty is created between the employee and the employer.
Arch.Design.s is thus listed among the companies that offer a bonus of choice for the recruitment of new employees and that are friendly to the family and through this program strengthens the marketing of HR.
The bone house still fascinates after 100 years. Take a look at Gaudi's interiors.
The roof resembles the back of a prehistoric saurian, the staircase to a dinosaur spine and the balconies to open fish mouths.
This is how is the Casa Battlo house in Barcelona by the architect Antoni Gaudi.
Due to its organic forms, the house received from the locals the nickname of Bone House.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stones, fragments of tiles and mosaic, fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade reminiscent of scales and everywhere present curves, this is all that is typical for Antoni Gaudi's Art Nouveau.
The front fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade of the house unfolds its dream lines, its pleasant colors and textures that recall nature and animals.
During a more detailed observation we see the geometry, the rhythm and the order thought with precision.
At night the fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade of the house becomes even more dramatic and is lit in such a way that the impression of brightness of the colors is reinforced.
The winding and twisting of the shapes also appears in the interiors with the same measure.
Wood waves copy window frames, balustrades, decorative elements of doors, eyelet and slats.
The Battlo house, which stands in the Eixample district on the Passeig de Gracia shopping street at number 43, was born from the construction of a house from 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortes.
The reconstruction took place for two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, Joseph Battlo, a wealthy entrepreneur, first insisted on the demolition of the old construction and the construction of another brand new one but quickly accepted Gaudi's idea of an unusual and cheaper reconstruction.
But the idea of Casa Battlo as a multi-dwelling house was not thought of by Gaudi alone.
The architect Josep Maria Jujol worked with him.
It is precisely on his project that the decorations for a representation apartment of the owner of the building and the use of the mosaic for the fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade were born.
For the fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade also worked other artists and creators.
The joint work for the plans of Casa Battlo began with a successful cooperation between Jujol and Gaudi.
Jujol participated in the construction of the house of Gaudi Casa Mila and the Park Guell in which there are other works of Gaudi.
Locals nicknamed the hot house just after its finish because of its organic shapes "the Bone House".
Others, given the specific mechanism of opening the windows, have called it "la maison qui baille".
It is said that at the top of the building there is a sword similar to that of Saint George the patron of Catalonia.
Other sculpture elements of the building contain hidden religious motifs.
Gaudi thought for the house a unique system in its central heating time, with ventilation vents and typical chimneys.
Their 45-degree inclination seems strange.
During the creation, Gaudi absolutely did not comply with the construction guidelines of the time and did not allow himself to be hindered by them.
At the beginning of the construction he obtained from the city the building permit, knowing, of course, that the data on the reconstruction plans were so vague that two years later during the completion the city council was horrified and asked for modifications.
For example, the members of the city council did not like the pillars of the construction to be encroached on the public sidewalk.
There was never a change, but, on the contrary, only 15 days after the call of the city Josep Battlo asked (and obtained satisfaction) permission to rent the two highest floors.
The owner moved to the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a common living room and on the third a bedroom and a private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The entire house of six floors is shared by a staircase through which you access to an independent roof terrace.
All right angles and straight lines were cancelled by the basic elements of the reconstruction and their replacement by curved walls.
Gaudi also worked on the modern concept of connecting spaces.
The common part can be completely connected by opening the doors of the lounges and the high society can communicate comfortably or limit the private space for more intimate interviews.
The house with the reconstruction of Gaudi has received a new facade a non-traditional roof and two floors in addition.
Gaudi’s play with the light is also impressive, blue and white glass tiles with which the inner courtyard is decorated and with the lighthouses.
The two-color play gives maximum light in all floors of the house.
It was simply enough to bet on the principle that white reflects more than dark, which on the contrary absorbs the rays of the sun.
The Casa Battlo house which was inscribed in 2005 in the UNESCO World Heritage Fund may be visited by everyone.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and splendid apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to take this step in 2002 on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous designer.
They continued the visits as they found it to be a lucrative business and they expanded the scope of visits to the common areas and attic including roof terraces.
The entrance ticket to the monument is really cheap and costs 16.50 euros; students, retirees, groups and tourist card holders have 20 percent discount.
The sum is still above the entry price in Gaudi's other constructions in the city.
If you want to feel the real atmosphere of the house with its fantastic turrets, you need to quickly find a comrade among the inhabitants of the building and visit the house completely.
