Devices to track people are increasingly in demand by parents who want to monitor their children.
Fear for their child leads more and more people to think about monitoring them through a GPS.
The system, initially set up to search for cars, can just as well be used to track people's movement and help in some cases, such as that of little Anicka Janatkova.
The instrument is currently as big as a match box but will soon be the size of a watch.
The case of little Anicka moved a large number of people and they began to look for ways to better protect their children.
Even if the price is to disturb their privacy.
"We are trying to tell everyone that this is not spying, but just another way to reduce the likelihood of another tragedy," said Petr Pilin of MAcro Weil, one of the Czech market's tracking equipment suppliers.
"I admit that there may be cases of misuse of such devices, such as putting it in the bag of a person who is not aware of it, but I have not yet encountered such cases."
“The majority of people are customers who actually buy the product for safety reasons,” Pilin adds.
According to him, children should always know what "box" is used for and how to use it in an emergency.
The children's psychologist, Dana Bockova, draws attention that if the child does not want to carry something of this type on him, he will get rid of it.
“And even the little ones can show great creativity when it comes to getting rid of something on purpose when they don’t want to be under control.”
“Mobile phones, which can cut off like these tracking devices, have already brought parents to long waits,” Bockova says.
According to her, the fact that this type of device can help in case of aggression is very questionable.
"If it's a prepared kidnapping, the author will do everything to ensure that the child doesn't have an electronic device that can locate him."
"At the moment, it's the phone."
"As soon as tracking devices develop, they (criminals) will also look for them because the sale will be supported by an advertising campaign."
"In such cases criminals will always be ahead of the police," said the psychologist.
She admits, however, that such devices can help in an attack not prepared by a pedophile.
According to Robert Cech of RC Monitoring, which offers tracking services for both cars and people, says that having this type of device can help, even if it is destroyed in the event of an assault.
"The device may be set to be in regular transmission after a specified period of time."
"In the event that the device is destroyed, there is still the last position of the person concerned."
"The more expensive devices also have an inclinometer that immediately indicates the position of the person who slipped and ends up in a lying position without moving," Cech said.
According to him, so-called smart mobile phones that are equipped with a navigation system, can offer a comparable service after having formatted it with a special software.
The problem with current tracking systems is that it is either a device similar to the ones that are pendant the size of a matchbox or to the smallest telephone devices.
We can always lose them.
According to Pilina of the company Macro Weil, this is why tests are currently being carried out to make devices that look like common digital watches.
"This will have the advantage that the potential attacker will not be able to recognize the tracing device."
"Either he will realize it after a while, which will have given the police a little more time," he added.
Whether the tracking device is developed in the form of a bracelet or pendant, it will always use the same technology as to track cars.
This is a combination of GPS position acquisition systems (usually used in autonavigation) and a cell phone function that alerts a vehicle to its current position.
