At the Land Fund in Plzen, the police carried out arrests during a public competition
In the building of the Land Fund in Plzen, the anti-corruption police have carried out arrests in recent days.
Detectives handed the handcuffs to the local contractor and real estate trader Lubos. G.
The latter had endeavoured to manipulate a public tender for the settlement of an application for restitution in such a way that the proposed land was obtained by a particular candidate.
He was to pay Lubos G. half a million crowns.
"For now I can only confirm that the police are prosecuting a person for an insider offense in the context of a public tender and competition," Plzen prosecutor Antonie Zelena told the newspaper Pravo, knowing that it is forbidden to provide further explanations because the investigation is ongoing.
The police released the 46-year-old contractor after 24 hours.
To find out how it could influence a public competition, one can only speculate in light of so little official information.
At a question from Pravo, the spokeswoman for the Lubomira Cerna Lands Fund said that the police had actually carried out an arrest in Plzen at a separate workplace during the public competition.
"It was a client and not an employee," she said.
The public competition according to Cerna has the real name "Call to propose rights for the transfer of land under the Land Act" and is put in place when several beneficiary candidates appear.
"These individuals propose, as part of the appeal, a higher value of their restitution rights that must be settled before the value of the land is announced."
"According to the proposed rights, a ranking of the buyers is set up and the Land Fund then transfers the land to the person who proposed the highest rights," the Fund's spokesman explained.
Lubos G. had, of course, the information concerning the persons who had registered for the appeal and, as he himself is, also one person benefitare because, having purchased a large number of restitution rights, he had proposed to the candidates on the ground not to participate in the competition.
And he was probably getting paid by retiring.
Which would explain why he had so much money in his possession at the time of his arrest.
Lubos G. had contacts well above the standards at the FdT (Fonds des Terrains).
It included the case of the former head of FDT Vaclav Sankot who was prosecuted for publishing land for which the decision to set up a construction had already been published.
For example, Lubos G. had obtained land for the construction of public communications, specifically in the place where the access artery to the industrial zone of Borske Pole was to be built.
Later he exchanged it with the town hall for a building in the historic center of the city whose value is far higher.
The town hall was obliged to accept because otherwise it risked putting the construction in jeopardy by blocking the land.
Households will pay an additional one hundred crowns per month for housing.
Households will have to pay an additional charge from January not only for all types of energy but also for water and sanitation, heating supplies and in some places rents will also increase.
As of January, families will have to draw up to a hundred crowns a month from their wallet.
Electricity increases by 4.6 percent, gas almost 2 percent more expensive, in some places you will have to pay up to a tenth of the water supply and in many places central heating supplies will also be more expensive.
The increase in electricity for apartment households is expected to be around 100 kronor more annually than at present.
However, all suppliers have lowered electricity prices given the sensitive development in encouraging the manufacture of renewable energies, particularly photovoltaic batteries.
Gas increases moderately but of course at a time when people need it most to heat and therefore have the greatest consumption.
One can also count a hundred more crowns.
Although electricity and gas are increasing throughout the Czech Republic, the change in the price of central heating differs from city to city.
It is mainly the largest municipalities that plan for price increases.
For example, households in Pardubice or Hradec Kraloce will pay nearly 50 more crowns per month for central heating from January, Liberec families will pay more than 1000 crowns annually.
For the inhabitants of Prague is preparing a 9 percent increase for water and sanitation in case the city increases the rents of infrastructure.
If the rents do not change the pragues will pay an additional 6.8 percent.
The price in Prague will still be among the lowest in comparison with the whole country.
In northern Bohemia, where prices are already among the highest, water and sanitation increase by 7.4 percent.
Rent prices will rise significantly in the 450,000 apartments to be rented from January, i.e. at the end of the regulation.
For example, the company CPI Byty, which owns almost 2500 apartments in Usti nad Labem, has decided to increase to 100 percent.
Those who disagree with the new rent increase will be brought before the courts by the company.
Regulated rents people pay in nearly 300,000 apartments could increase by 10 percent next year.
Czech children get drunk with rum and fernet. Beer is no longer in fashion and acts very gently.
Fernet, rum, vodka and exceptionally also the best brand of whisky are stolen from parents.
These are drinks that most often bring those who are drunk, who are not yet fifteen years old, into the hands of the doctor.
Children who are treated in hospital for recidivism are no exception.
This is the result of the experience of doctors who encounter cases similar to admissions from children's departments of hospitals.
“Beers or wines are no longer fashionable because it takes time to be drunk.”
"The trend is really to strong alcohols," says Pravo Ludek Pelikan, Head of the Children's Department at Horovice Hospital in Central Bohemia.
"When they manage to chip a daddy bottle in the closet, it's sometimes whisky but it's fernet and vodka that prevail."
"Vodka has this advantage that they can mix it with fruit juice and thus not smell it," explains the head of the department.
Eva Jurinova, spokeswoman for Motol Hospital, also said she was right.
"Usually it's rum or fernet."
"It's now alcohol in fashion, especially in elementary schools."
"In some cases, it was slivovice that they brought back from the house," Jurinova added.
According to the head of the Pelikan department, seeing drunken children aged 13 to 14 on hospital admissions is a normal phenomenon.
Before working in Horovice since last year, he was in Motol where he worked for 10 years in pediatrics, where ambulances brought schoolchildren from completely drunken areas.
A young girl was hospitalized four times.
"She started her career at the age of twelve when she was brought with 3.5 per thousand alcohol in the blood with a mixture with ecstasy," the doctor described this particularly important case.
"She was at the Holesovice Exhibition Centre at a party."
"What's interesting is that it didn't seem strange to the mother that her daughter was absent for 48 hours," said the Director of the Department.
It is precisely the disinterestedness of the parents or their unusual tolerance for the fact that their offspring indulge in drinking that are the main cause of the development of children's alcoholism.
According to specialists, however, there is no talk of addiction, in its strict sense, for children.
"Under the term alcoholic we hear a chronic dependence on alcohol for several years with all the phenomena that result but that we do not find in children."
"For those who use acool repeatedly, it is rather a significantly unfavourable socio-family background," Pelikan said.
According to spokeswoman Jurinova, about forty drunk children were hospitalized this year until mid-November at the pediatric clinic in Motol.
Only cases with severe intoxication requiring hospitalization are included in the statistics.
Drunk children who are brought home after emergency care by parents or police are not counted.
In addition to the cases of children who sit down and drink a bottle of alcohol after school, according to Pelikan, he excites three seasonal waves that can be counted on: Witch's Day, Saint Sylvester and the end of the school year.
"Either they drink in spite of bad results or on the contrary, they celebrate the beginning of the holiday."
"Of course, I experienced the admission of seven drunk children at once on Witch Day," Pelikan said.
The drunken child who spent the night in the hospital in detoxification under medical supervision is paradoxically in a better position than the one who went home and suffers the day after the "hangover".
Morning headaches caused by dehydration and a lack of glucose are eliminated by an infusion of glucose and nutrients that the body needs.
"They are better off for this because they have a great evening and then a gentle awakening and nothing hurts them."
“They’re just amazed at where they’re at,” Pelikan adds, knowing that from time to time it spoils patients’ good mood at least with the bill to pay for their care.
Ambulance transportation and intensive care bed hospitalization can go up to tens of thousands of crowns.
“Once in a while, I have applied this as a means of education by telling these children how much their drunkenness has cost and that they could spend the whole summer in seasonal work to reimburse a single evening,” Pelikan added.
However, according to him, health insurance companies in their regressive management, which should recover from parents the burdens of care, do not deal with cases of drunk children.
Two L-159 aircraft are for the first time in foreign hands in Spain.
Two of the five L-159 aircraft, for which the Ministry of Defense exchanged Casa C-295M transport aircraft, took off on Tuesday to Seville, Spain, where the aircraft manufacturer Casa-EADS is based.
This is the first time such aircraft have become the property of someone other than the Czech army.
However, they have been abroad as part of exercises or demonstration flights.
These are the two-seater versions of the L-159T1 that were previously in service in the Czech army and were in a state of flight.
The remaining three devices are single-seater versions of the L-159.
These are currently parked at Aero Vodochody and the commercial intermediary - Omnipol - took them into account last week.
According to Jan Pejsek of the Ministry of Defense’s press department, the physical departure of Vodochody’s planes is currently unknown.
"The L-159 single-seater aircraft intended for exchange were taken on long-storage aircraft without causing any additional burdens or investments for the Ministry of Defence."
"The L-159 T1 two-seaters were exchanged in the state," Pejsek told Pravo.
He argued that the military would not be without two-seaters as the ministry signed in May 2009 with Aéro Vodochody an agreement worth 200 million crowns for the transformation of four unused L-159 single-seaters into two-seaters.
The army took delivery of the first aircraft in July, with the second scheduled for delivery later this year.
According to Pejsek EADS pledged to introduce the aircraft into the equipment of certain Alliance countries.
"The contract clearly states that the L-159 aircraft are EADS and will be used to train pilots from NATO member countries."
"It is therefore up to the one who is considering how to do this," Pejsek said.
Hospodarske noviny announced some time ago that the Spanish army is not interested in the L-159.
The exchange of five L-159s for a Casa aircraft and the purchase of three more aircraft for 3.5 billion crowns was endorsed last year by the government of Mirek Topomanek.
The Ministry of Defence did not call for tenders and contacted EADS directly.
The defense leadership then argued that the exchange ensures future export of the L-159 overseas.
The Czech army bought from Aero Vodochody 72 aircraft and only uses 24, wanting to sell the rest.
The purchase of Casa planes will likely have legal implications.
However, the European Commission has filed a complaint against the Czech Ministry of Defence with the European Court of Justice because the aircraft should have been selected as part of a European-wide tender and under no circumstances by contacting a manufacturer directly.
The army has already taken delivery of three Casa planes, the last is expected to arrive at Prague Kbely airport in two weeks.
A longer index than the annular is a sign of low cancer risk
Men who have the index longer than the annular are at a lower risk of having prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published Wednesday by the British magazine Cancer.
This can depend on the level of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our findings show that the relative length of the finger serves as a simple prostate cancer risk test, especially for men before age 60," said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help determine which men should be tested for prostate cancer, including by combining it with genetic risk or other aggravating factors such as family health history, Eeles added.
During the period 1994-2009 she followed up with her colleagues in Britain more than 1500 patients with prostate cancer and at the same time nearly three thousand healthy men.
More than half of the participants in the study had the index of the right hand shorter than the ring finger.
For them as for the 19 percent of those who had fingers of the same length, we found the same probability of prostate cancer.
In the case of those who had the index longer than the annular the risk fell to 33 percent, however, for men before 60 the decrease in risk reached 87 percent.
The length ratio of the two fingers mentioned - formed during the prenatal period - indicates in particular different levels of sex hormones to which the child is exposed in the uterus.
Unless testosterone corresponds to a longer index.
Previous research had shown that it is testosterone that helps in the development of prostate cancer.
Professor Vacla Paces, a renowned Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, told CTK that he is aware of this study but that it does not appear to him that the relationship between finger length and cancer is "completely demonstrated".
