Prosecutors will not indict Senator Ensign
Justice Department prosecutors have lifted criminal charges against Senator John Ensign, arising from a case related to a former campaign assistant and his efforts to get a lobbying job for the woman's husband, the senator's lawyers said Wednesday.
The decision ends the most serious legal threat faced by Mr. Ensign, the Nevada Republican who was considered a possible Republican presidential candidate in 2012 until the scandal around his case made national headlines last year and hurt his career.
Mr. Ensign's office said he was "very happy" with the decision, the result of a one-year investigation.
The honourable senator may still be exposed to disciplinary action by the Senate Ethics Committee.
Mr. Ensign's lawyers stated that the Department of Justice had "informed that Senator Ensign was no longer the subject of the investigation and that he did not intend to maintain any charges against him in this case."
The Department of Justice abstained from commenting on the matter.
The announcement came as a sort of surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Department of Justice that there was significant evidence that Mr. Ensign allegedly conspired to violate a federal criminal ban on lobbying.
Interviews, emails and other documents, first released in October 2009 in the New York Times, indicated that Mr. Ensign had helped Douglas Hampton, who was one of his assistants, get a lucrative lobbying job to gain silence from Mr. Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, about the senator's affair with her.
Ms. Hampton once served as a Treasurer during an Ensign campaign.
Mr. Ensign contacted a number of political donors to find work for Mr. Hampton and then defended their rights after they hired Mr. Hampton to lobby for them; according to documents and interviews.
Since Mr. Hampton had recently been an employee of Mr. Ensign, he was prohibited by law from lobbying with his former employer or the Senate as a whole for a year.
Ethics experts have argued that the unusual agreement between Mr. Ensign and Mr. Hampton, who were close friends before the case, appears to be in contradiction to the so-called lobbying revolving door ban.
“There appears to be prima facie evidence of a conspiracy to violate and materially violate the rotating door law,” said Stanley Brand, a Washington attorney who specializes in defending clients from a government investigation.
Although the department's judge refused to explain the reasoning that led to the decision in Ensign's case, Brand and other ethics lawyers said the department appeared to be wary of political prosecution after a number of high-level setbacks cashed out by its public integrity section, including Steven's decision last year to drop T's prosecution.
Federal prosecutors are clearly afraid to take up arms, said Melanie Sloan, the Director General of Citizens’ Responsibility and Ethics in Washington, a defense group that has received several complaints against Mr. Ensign in the case.
"This basically says high-ranking government officials can now assume the laws don't apply to them," she added.
Paul Coggins, senior lawyer for Ensign, said in an interview that he received a phone call Monday from a Justice Department prosecutor and follow-up the next day, telling him that the ministry was not looking for charges against his client.
Mr. Ensign's team of lawyers had cooperated with prosecutors to try to persuade them that the senator, as his office reaffirmed Wednesday in a statement, "had acted in accordance with the law."
Mr. Coggins refused to clarify the legal arguments he had made to the prosecutor.
“I’m not comfortable going into the details of my discussions with the Department of Justice except to say that we think they’ve made the right decision,” he said.
Last month, the Federal Elections Commission decided to abandon an investigation following an independent complaint by the ethics group, arguing that Mr. Ensign's payment of $96,000 by his parents to the Hamptons violated federal electoral law.
The electoral commission said it did not have enough evidence to prove that the money was anything but a gift.
NV Energy, a major Nevada company that has long supported the senator, is a company for which Mr. Ensign helped Mr. Hampton find lobbying work.
An email sent in December 2008 showed that, after the company welcomed Mr. Hampton as a lobbyist, Mr. Ensign's chief of staff, John Lopez, contacted Mr. Hampton and told him that he was "hammering" the Home Office on a disputed issue.
Mr. Ensign also participated in a lunch with Mr. Hampton and another Nevada client, Allegiant Air, and he asked the Secretary of Transportation to arrange a meeting on behalf of the airline after engaging Mr. Hampton in lobbying.
When news of the case surfaced last year, Mr. Ensign apologized to his constituents and resigned from his fourth-ranking Republican leadership position in the Senate.
After maintaining a low profile for several months, Mr. Ensign said two weeks ago that he intends to run for a third term in the Senate.
Announcing that Mr. Ensign was no longer the target of a criminal investigation, his spokesman, Jennifer Cooper, said the senator hoped that the ethics committee would quickly follow the example of the Department of Justice and end its investigation.
Senator Ensign looks forward to continuing his hard work on behalf of the people of Nevada, she said.
