Can civility bring the divides closer together?
After a campaign marked by invectiveness and negativity, a minimum of civility erupted in Washington this week.
Is this a warning sign of true bipartisan cooperation forward or an illusory moment before the rapid return to partisan struggle in the capital?
Tuesday’s meeting between President Obama and congressional leaders produced no breakthrough on the big issues that need to be addressed during the “lame duck” session.
But obviously, there was at least one polite discussion on the differences between the two sides as well as on the recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than another episode where each side wanted to score points.
The public meeting of Wednesday’s committee on the president’s deficit was equally civilized, despite the political divergences that remain between members.
It seems clear that the close interaction of several months has created a mutual respect transcending the ideological gap; but that, however, still divides the members.
This is hardly enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
The two sides are now in a period of mutual trial and testing for signs of cooperation and compromise, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and voter patience for a renewed partisan war.
That's why Tuesday's meeting and subsequent comments from participants revealed a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and Republicans are too great and too deep to suggest a rapid climate change that has existed over the past two years.
Whether it's taxation, spending, health care or fees, both sides are miles away.
Yet the November election had moderated Washington, at least in the short term.
“There is no doubt that things have changed in the tone,” said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official, now alongside the Center for Ethical and Public Policy.
“This is inevitable after the elections.
Elections provoke partisan passions and then they fade.
That's good."
On some issues, including those on the agenda of the "lame duck" session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush’s tax cuts will expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favor of that.
Both sides want to find a way to preserve some or all of it, permanently or temporarily.
Likewise, a compromise is envisaged on extending unemployment benefits, if only because Republicans cannot afford to give the impression that they are in favour of tax cuts for the rich, while denying unemployment benefits to unemployed workers.
After Tuesday's meeting in the White House, more optimism is hovering over a possible agreement on issues raised during the session on the "lame duck", with the ratification of the "New START" pact.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation on the most pressing issues of the "lame duck" session will not necessarily lead to a better understanding between the two parties when the 112th Congress meets in January.
Instead, he says, a period of disagreement is likely, if not inevitable.
“Once the things that need to be done are done, psychology in the short term will return to one of the confrontations,” he said.
Wehner also expressed his widely shared skepticism that civility would lead to genuine cooperation.
"I consider most of what happens between now and 2012 as a pre-show or shadow-boxing compared to the main event of 2012," he said.
The reasons for this are closely related to the composition of the new Republican majority in the House and the tea voters who contributed to its creation.
However, Republican leaders are aware of the dangers if they go too far, they know that they must try to live up to their promises to cut public spending and repeal the new health care law.
These partisan positions are already clear in the initial reactions to the recommendations of the deficit committee that include reforming the tax code and raising certain taxes, pushing the retirement age and reducing spending.
Co-chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles chose one of the toughest tasks in Washington and, according to them, imposed the issue of the deficit on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the 18-member commission to issue their plan as an official recommendation, and they have struggled to reach that number.
The greatest resistance remains among the group's elected officials, suggesting that there are few grounds for or willingness to compromise on tax matters, at least today.
Galston predicts two phases in the fighting between the White House and Congressional Republicans.
The first will come next year in the form of partisan clashes, as Republicans challenge Obama in terms of budget, taxes and health care; then it will be followed by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What would be the cause of the change?
The public opinion.
It is widely proven that, despite the spirit of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties work together.
If the confrontation leads to a stalemate, as in 1995, then both parties will closely observe the reaction of the public.
The one who will be judged in loss will have to change course and find compromises.
However, that would be an optimistic view.
The partisan spirit and polarization are greater today than they were in the mid-1990s and there seems to be a greater ideological gap between Obama and Congressional Republicans than there was then between President Bill Clinton and Republicans.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as a mere prelude to a more consistent election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civility exposed this week could be appreciated by many Americans.
But it will take much more effort on the part of both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
Leaked U.S. documents describe Moscow as a haven of corruption
The control of the city is in the hands of a "Kleptocracy" and passes to the Kremlin some of the bribes and protection money it collects, the U.S. embassy in Russia reported in a note in February.
The police and the Federal Security Service are carrying out huge rackets that help explain the high cost of living in Moscow, he said.
They collect money not only from legitimate companies but also from organized criminal groups.
Every layer of bureaucracy – what Prime Minister Vladimir Putin called the “vertical of power” – takes its share as money moves up the ladder.
The memo, which was sent to Washington under the name of Ambassador John Beyrle, was posted Wednesday by Wikileaks on its website.
The note is based on sources whose names have been purged.
It was written while Yuri Luzhkov was still the mayor of Moscow; and he is largely held responsible for corruption.
He was fired in October by President Dmitry Medvedev, but since then there have been few traces of clean-up.
