In September, he told a Russian television channel, when asked about a documentary suggesting he was corrupt: “It’s crazy, it’s throwing, it’s anything.”
The Russians believe, with an overwhelming majority, that their society is corrupt; according to polls.
But it is unusual to find the information set out in an embassy report; and it is unheard of to conceive that it would be to diplomats from a foreign country to do so.
The direct link between the Moscow city government and crime has led some people to call it "dysfunctional" and claim that the government functioned more like a kleptocracy than a government," according to the embassy note.
The criminal elements enjoy a "krysha" (a term used in the criminal/mafia world which literally means "roof" or protection) that passes through the police, the Federal Security Service (FSB), the Ministry of the Interior (MVD) and the prosecutor's office, as well as through the entire bureaucracy of the Moscow city government.
"Analysts identify a three-tier structure in the criminal world of Moscow."
"Luzhkov is at the top."
"The FSB, the MVD and the militias are on the second level."
“Finally, ordinary criminals and corrupt inspectors are at the lowest level.”
“This is an ineffective system in which criminal groups fill a gap in some areas where the city does not provide certain services.”
The report indicates that the FSB is brewing the money of the largest companies and that the police are targeting the small ones.
One source, he said, "explained that Moscow business owners understood that it was better to get protection from the MVD and FSB (rather than organized crime groups) because not only do they have more weapons, more means, and more power than criminal groups, but they are also protected by law."
“That’s why the demand for protection by criminal gangs is no longer as high.”
The note notes that although the collection of money is extended, the protection itself may be unequal; even those who pay are sometimes subject to arrest.
Those who do not pay quickly see their business shut down under one pretext or another.
