In a poorly lit classroom with decaying, poor-quality concrete walls, the headmaster of Anlong Veng High School evoked the man who built it, the last Khmer Rouge leader, Ta Mok.
"Everyone here loves your mok."
“He was a good leader; and he cared for his people,” said Sreng Kor Ma, 42.
Known as "the butcher" for his brutality, when he was at the head of the Khmer Rouge, this commander remains popular in this isolated stronghold of former Khmer Rouge in northwestern Cambodia where he built hospitals, bridges and other infrastructure; and where thousands of former Khmer Rouge soldiers still live today.
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge surrendered to the government, the longstanding loyalty to Anlong Veng is finally called into question.
In April, a local truth and reconciliation forum enabled victims to face the people who had participated in the regime publicly.
In June, the government distributed a high school textbook that, for the first time, teaches the history of the Khmer Rouge to the children of its former soldiers.
And in July, a Cambodian court, jointly led by the United Nations, issued its first sentence against a former Khmer Rouge member, sentenced to 35 years in prison the former head of the infamous Tuol Sleng torture center, Kaing Khek Yev, better known as "Duch".
Faced with this evolution of the situation, anxiety increased among the Khmer Rouge veterans of Anlong Veng; complicating reconciliation efforts and their willingness to reintegrate into Cambodian society.
“There is resentment and fear among the former Khmer Rouge, but they are powerless to do anything,” said Chhang Youk, director of the Cambodia Documentation Centre, an independent body conducting research on the regime.
For them, life under the Khmer Rouge was glorious, but the regime has become a symbol of evil.
"The situation creates divisions within families."
During the Khmer Rouge reign in Cambodia, from 1975 to 1979, about 1.7 million people were executed or died of hunger, illness or overwork.
When the Vietnamese invaded and overthrew the United Pol Pot government in 1979, the rest of the regime and its army fled to the Cambodian border with Thailand.
There, they launched an insurrection that lasted until the last of the movements surrendered in December 1998.
While Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary led the guerrilla base in the western mountains of Cambodia and in the jungle, Ta Mok was preparing a sequel to Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, after a UN-sponsored peace agreement led to the country's first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of Khmer Rouge fighters began to defect to government, culminating with the capitulations of Ieng Sary in 1996 and Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998 and Ta Mok, who had stood up, was captured by government forces in 1999 in the mountains near Dangrek.
He died in a Phnom Penh prison in 2006 awaiting trial.
Without their benefactors, most of the Khmer Rouge veterans have sunk into the black misery common to rural Cambodia; and many remain nostalgic for the movement.
Although some Khmer Rouge elite officers kept their positions as local leaders in exchange for laying down the weapons, they are unskilled farmers of low rank and record.
"These people have had very little follow-up after the surrender," said Sok Leang of the Centre for Justice and Reconciliation, which holds public forums throughout Cambodia, including in Anlong Veng.
"They are soaked in the utopian agrarian ideology of the regime."
"They were raised in a setting where doing business is a foreign concept."
Sor Lim, 55, who joined the Khmer Rouge as a teenager in 1974, fought in the jungle around Anlong Veng before settling in 1998 as a poor rice farmer.
“Life under the Khmer Rouge was good,” he said.
"Your Mok feeds everyone."
But now life is difficult because we have to provide for our own needs.”
The ongoing Khmer Rouge tribunal has also raised concerns here.
The court is expected to begin the trial of Nuon Chea, Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, Ieng Thirith, another former Khmer Red minister, at the beginning of next year.
The court’s mandate is to try senior leaders and those responsible for the crimes, but it did not say whether it continued beyond these four cases.
It would take more to calm the fears in Anlong Veng.
The latest media speculation turned to 64-year-old Im Chaem, a former district chief in Banteay Meanchey province during the Khmer Rouge rule in the 1970s.
In 2007, she told researchers at the Cambodia Documentation Centre that she had overseen the construction of the Trapeang Thma dam, a project where thousands of forced labourers allegedly died.
Recently, on a hot evening, Im Chaem was returning from work to the field located near his wooden house on poles, on a dirt road outside Anlong Veng.
As the sun cast long shadows on the dried grass, Im Chaem refused to discuss his past within the Khmer Rouge.
If the court called her, she said, she would refuse to go.
“Cambodia is at peace and stable,” she said.
"If there are more prosecutions, there will be war."
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who defected from the Khmer Rouge in 1978, has also repeatedly warned that instability would occur if the court prosecuted several suspects; although experts and historians dispute this.
“Cambodia must dig a hole and bury the past,” he said.
But confronting the past is all Cambodia needs to do to move forward, says Youk Chhang of the documentation center.
"The reconciliation in Khmer terms is to reconnect the broken pieces," he said.
“We need to put these pieces together so we can understand.”
The center produced the first government-approved manual on the Khmer Rouge, "A History of Democratic Kampuchea, composed of 75 pages."
He distributed it in Anlong Veng in June as a supplement to the Ministry of Education's history textbooks, designed for high schools, which contained less than four pages on the Khmer Rouge.
As in most of Cambodia, the young people of Anlong Veng know only a few details about the Khmer Rouge, despite the city's ties to the regime.
Touch Valeak, 19, a student at Anlong Veng High School, said the new handbook helped students understand an important part of their story.
But his parents reacted with skepticism when he returned with the book home to study.
“My family rejects many parts of the manual and the court,” he said.
“They’re wary because they don’t know exactly how many people the court will sue.”
Such resistance has made the reconciliation process complex and difficult, Sok Leang said.
But public forums, the manual, and the court are beginning to have an impact, he said.
Yet the Khmer Rouge retains a powerful appeal here.
In the heights of the Dangrek Mountains, a path, invaded by weeds and dotted with plastic bags, leads up to a rectangle of black soot, covered with a roof of rusted sheet metal.
Pol Pot's body was burned here on a pile of tires after his death in 1998.
Nuom Sothea, a 31-year-old mobile phone seller on the roadside, said she didn’t know much about the man who was cremated there.
"But he has a great spirit; and many inhabitants go there to pray," she said.
It was Nuom Sothea's birthday and later that day she planned to walk to Pol Pot's last resting place where she would leave a bunch of ripe bananas in the hope of bringing luck.
