Sport and fraud of the law
The tricks similar to that of Alonso and Ramos against Ajax demonstrate the ingenuity but not the willingness to escape a sanction.
The expulsion in principle by two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) during the match on November 23 against Ajax in the Champions League drew a lot of ink on the unsportsmanship of such behavior and whether both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As we know, a few minutes before the end of the game (which their team was already clearly winning), both players deliberately lost their time when they made mistakes to determine the referee to show them the second yellow card.
Thus, and given that Real Madrid will eventually be the leader of his group, both players will meet the regulatory penalty during the next game of the dam game against Auxerre and will be able to move without cards to the next phase.
Finally, the UEFA Discipline Committee sanctioned team coach José Mourinho with two games and various financial sums to the players involved.
The provocation of a yellow card in circumstances like this or similar is not a new practice, if not rather common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, the unwritten rules, but followed, of this sport.
Part of the debate emerged in the related case is due to the fact that this had as the protagonist a team of the entity of Real Madrid (who in his anthem displays nobility and honor and who in past occasions sentenced his players to a fine for similar acts) and to the dramatization orchestrated, apparently, by Mourinho, which adds a more episode to his story.
In any case, the debate asks whether this type of behaviour is not expressly prohibited by the regulation in contradiction to the principles of sport, that is, if these actions are committed to fraud by law; because, in fact, they are actions respectful of the sporting regulations, but seem to circumvent its meaning.
The question is to examine the type of harm they cause to the sporting mind.
One of the assets that includes the sporting spirit is the physical integrity of the opposing players, an aspect that with these actions has not been endangered, that is, there has been no violent play.
Another asset that is alluded to with correct play is to prevent the infringing team from unfairly benefiting the opposing team, which is not the case either.
However, the paradoxical fact of the action of Real Madrid players is that it does not conform to what is normally described as cheating or fraud of the law, because its violation of the rules was not carried out in hiding to try to avoid the penalty, but their action precisely tried to be as obvious as possible to receive the penalty from the referee.
They waited and they gladly accepted the sanction.
Another issue is the type of advantage that offenders get from the intentional misconduct examined.
Here it seems necessary to note that one does not put the opponent in a disadvantage situation and one does not get an advantage in the same match either, because obviously the result of the action involves leaving their own team with fewer players.
And it's not a useful strategy for the next game either, because the club couldn't count on these players.
Obviously the advantage is that players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future game.
But this is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of indeterminacy, because the team could be eliminated suddenly and apart from that, with this action the players complete a penalty game and move to the second cycle of cards, in which the suspension due to the accumulation of cards occurs with a less than in the first cycle.
So, climbing the steps is not so clear that this is an advantage.
Ultimately, these actions are not at odds with the spirit of sport, which is still part of making strategic decisions that promote profit to the maximum of what the rules allow.
In our case, the players did not act to avoid the application of the penalty (this would indeed be a clear case of fraud of the law), but they chose instead the time when they submitted to it.
They made a strategic decision without overcoming the penalty or running away from it.
Even though the boundary between genius and law fraud is diffuse, on this occasion I think we have had a clear case of genius.
The controversy, it seems to me, arises because of two factors: because there have been two self-expulsions and because of the way to transmit the director to provoke them.
The evil caused to the principles of sport by these actions is not as ethical as it is aesthetic.
