The European Union changes the rules for obtaining a visa
Individuals must go to Visa Applicant Service Centres prior to their interview in the Consular Section; the cost of waiting time will be reduced.
As of January 10, 2011, the procedure for processing visas at the U.S. Embassy and Consulates will change.
With the new procedure, the majority of applicants will have to submit to the Visa Applicant Service Centres (Visa Applicant Service Centres, ASC) prior to their interview at the Consular Section.
CSA staff will take the applicant's biometric information, which will be reviewed by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have some advantages for applicants, including the following:
The total cost for processing the visa will be lower, it will no longer be necessary to make a payment to get an appointment, another payment for processing the visa and another for the courier service to deliver the document.
The applicant will make a one-time payment that will cover all three services.
The current rate will remain the same: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visas with application (including visas for temporary workers) and $390 for visas for traders and investors.
Individuals wishing to renew their visa will not have to attend an interview with the Consular Representative, they will only present themselves to the nearest ASC where they will present the documents and take their fingerprints.
Due to the fact that biometric information will be taken in the CSA, applicants who want a second appointment to be interviewed in the Consular Section will stay there less time than before.
Similarly, visa applicants at the Consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra service fee of $26.
For more information on the new visa application procedure, visit the following page: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/bulletines/sp101201_Visum-FAQs.html
