450 million in contracts without tender
Hydro-Québec has awarded over-the-counter $450 million in contracts to engineering firms for the Eastmain-1-A-Sarcelle-Rupert hydroelectric project.
At the heart of this avalanche of more than 100 contracts, it is a consortium formed by the firms BPR, Dessau, Groupe SM and Axor that has obtained the largest, that of the project management, for a sum of 295 million dollars without a tender.
This consortium called Managed Energy was formed in 2004 in conjunction with Hydro-Québec's choice to entrust the private sector with its responsibility for managing this $5 billion hydroelectric project.
At the beginning of 2005, the Energy Managed Consortium was awarded the lucrative contract without a public tender.
For the Parti Québécois, the use of business consortia poses a serious ethical problem that risks eliminating competition and causing prices to rise.
"That's the new way to collusion and knock down the competition."
“In other words, people, instead of doing it secretly, are now doing it openly,” said Sylvain Simard, a member of parliament for the Pécs, at a press conference.
Earlier in the morning, Mr. Simard raised the issue in the National Assembly because he said he hardly saw how the public interest could be served in this way.
The Minister of Natural Resources, Nathalie Normandeau, replied in the afternoon, vigorously denying that there was collusion for this contract.
“I’m starting to have my trip,” she said, arguing that the PQ had been “dishonest” and “lacked rigour.”
She said that "it would be the least thing" that the PQ apologizes for.
The consortium formula is a common practice around the world.
This is usually a time-limited alliance that allows two or more companies to pool their respective expertise to respond to a call for tenders for a complex project.
The Eastmain project has a high level of complexity given the magnitude of the work.
The project is underway and is scheduled to run until 2012.
However, the contract was awarded without the competition acting; there was negotiation.
Therefore, the consortium formula is no longer an exception in Quebec, even for relatively simple projects.
As revealed last week in Le Devoir, the consulting engineering consortium formula is being investigated by the government.
A quick survey of the Quebec business register allows to count more than 200 consortia, some of which seem permanent.
Thus, Dessau works in partnership with most of its main competitors, including CIMA+, Génivar, SNC-Lavalin and other Roche and Tecsult.
Each combination, and there are dozens, brings back to one and the same legal person, or Dessau.
Regarding the Energy Managed Consortium, Minister Normandeau pointed out that "the James Bay territory responds to particular labour dynamics and that Hydro-Québec has responded in a particular way since the 1970s".
The great Eastmain project boss, Réal Laporte, of the James Bay Energy Society (SEBJ), gave an explanation that made it blunt that the project's stewardship contract was granted on an over-the-counter basis.
"If you go to the tender and there are few bidders, your prices will be higher."
"You have two choices: either you take the people who are in that market and you say: we're going to negotiate a satisfactory agreement and at a good price."
“But the idea is that it is not the price that is important, it is the competence of the people,” Laporte said.
This contract awarded to the Energy Management Consortium is part of a long list of contracts of more than $50,000 obtained by the Parti Québécois.
The contracts were awarded by Hydro-Québec or SEBJ for the Eastmain-1-A-Sarcelle-Rupert project.
After verification, Le Devoir counted 109 consulting engineering contracts awarded between 2002 and March 2010 to firms or their subsidiaries, including soil laboratories.
SNC-Lavalin has won 22 contracts, Génivar has 16, Tecsult 14 and Dessau 10, not to mention its participation in Energy Managed.
All contracts have been negotiated.
They total $449,783,344, including the Managing Energy contract of $295,131,564.
Sylvain Simard suggested that the four firms that make up the consortium (BPR, Dessau, Groupe SM and Axor) are "well known to the Quebec Liberal Party".
Minister Normandeau dropped that the PQ is also linked to those firms that "finance" it, before clarifying that it was rather its leaders.
