Although they increased consumption of so-called socially responsible products in 2010, Quebecers seem to give very little credit to those who are trying to sell them.
Two-thirds of them say they do not believe the environmental commitment of companies as well as the green advertising of companies, reveals the measurement tool developed by the Observatory of Responsible Consumption of Sherbrooke University.
Another finding: half of consumers doubt the reliability of official certifications affixed to so-called fair products, but also the credibility of products and brands showing themselves as eco-responsible, says the Barometer.
In the same vein, the discourse of politicians on this topic is taken seriously by only 14.6% of Quebecers.
However, information on responsible consumption seems essential to stimulate this part of consumption currently driven by almost a third of Quebec's consumers.
Indeed, the emptiness and doubtful nature of information would calm the ardours of 46% of consumers.
This is the second brake identified by the Barometer, after the higher price of these products.
In addition, a third of Quebecers say they are also suspicious of the alleged performance of the green products or services they are trying to get into their hands.
On another note, nearly half of consumers in 2010 changed their habits and, most importantly, changed brands of one or more products to meet their conviction.
As much as 61%, they also favored purchases from traders in their neighborhood and preferred the purchase of food products grown in their region, says the Barometer.
More green and responsible – the Responsible Consumption Index has reached 64 out of a maximum of 100 for this year – the Homo consumus du Québec likes to present itself as the king of recycling that seeks to reduce its environmental footprint by caring for the protection of animals.
But his social and ecological conscience seems to remain outside his car, says the Barometer: in 2010, only 28% of Quebecers reported using public transport or advocated carpooling to defend their green interests.
Walking and cycling were also supported by 39.1% of participants in this vast behavioral survey, which has just taken its first shot.
