Unemployment rate in France remained stable in the third quarter
The unemployment rate in France within the meaning of the International Labour Office (ILO) remained stable at 9.3% in the metropolis (9.7% by counting the overseas departments), show the provisional seasonally adjusted data (CVS) published Thursday by the INSEE.
The number of unemployed is 2.631 million in the metropolis.
The second quarter data were confirmed to 9.3% of the working population in the metropolis and 9.7% with the DOMs.
Over a year, the unemployment rate increased by 0.1 point.
More broadly, 3.4 million people in metropolitan France did not work in the third quarter but wanted to work, whether or not they were available within two weeks to work and whether or not they were looking for a job.
The situation of young people in the labour market has further deteriorated, with a further increase in the unemployment rate, rising to 24.2% in the metropolis (+0.9 points over three months, +0.5 points over a year) and 25% including the DOMs.
In the third quarter, 637,000 youth aged 15 to 24 were unemployed within the meaning of the ILO.
Seniors, for their part, experienced a slight increase in unemployment, to 6.4% in the metropolis (+0.2 points over three months as well as over a year), i.e. 482,000 people aged 50 or older, and 6.6% with the DOMs.
Only 25-49-year-olds benefited from stable unemployment in the third quarter, at 8.3% in the metropolis (-0.1 points over three months, +0.1 points over a year) and 8.8% throughout France.
The INSEE has not published monthly unemployment rates since 2006, after a controversy over its method of calculation.
Eurostat, the European Union's statistical agency, on the other hand, continues to do so and announced on Tuesday a rate of 9.8% for France (including the DOM) in October after 9.9% in September.
