A diplomatic telegram written on 12 August 2009 in Paris is entitled "Iran: French comments on how to handle hostage cases".
The Elysée’s advisor for strategic affairs, Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Richier, accompanied by the director of the Quai d’Orsay for North Africa and the Middle East, Patrice Paoli, meets with U.S. diplomat Kathleen Allegrone.
They explain the French method.
They advise Americans to do the same to repatriate their own forcibly detained nationals to Iran.
"Make noise," they say, "continuously hammer" in the media the words "fundamental human rights", " innocence", "immediate liberation".
It is necessary in order to embarrass the Iranian regime, sensitive to its image.
“Do it all the more because the Iranians are asking you not to do it.”
Because, after attempts to talk through discreet channels, “the silence will not settle anything,” the Iranians are “masters in delaying maneuvers.”
Richier added that the arrest of foreigners was “a familiar Iranian tactic: taking hostages for political blackmail.”
