Avengers and spies in due diligence
The WikiLeaks case has a double value.
On the one hand, it turns out to be an apparent scandal, a scandal that appears as a scandal only in the face of the hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it heralds profound changes at the international level, and foreshadows a future dominated by regression.
But let's proceed in order.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation of the fact that every file made up by a secret service (of any nation) is composed exclusively of press cuts.
The "extraordinary" American revelations about Berlusconi's sexual habits only report what could have been read in any newspaper for months (except those owned by Berlusconi), and Gaddafi's sinisterly caricatured profile has long been for sketch-material cabaret artists.
The rule that secret files should only be composed of new ones already known is essential to the dynamics of the secret services, and not only in this century.
If you go to a bookstore dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each work repeats exactly what was already written in earlier works (on the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Ch<0xC3><0xA2>teau, the Templars or the Rose Cross).
And this is not only because the author of occult texts does not like to do unpublished research (or knows where to look for news on the inexperienced), but because those who engage in occultism only believe in what they already know, and that reconfirms what they had already learned.
This is the mechanism of Dan Brown’s success.
Same for the secret files.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or limited-minded) the head of the secret services (otherwise he could be, what do I know, editor at Liberation), who retains as true only what he recognizes.
The top secret information about Berlusconi that the U.S. embassy in Rome sent to the State Department was the same as Newsweek published the week before.
So why did the revelations on these files make so much noise?
On the one hand, they say what every educated person already knows, namely that embassies, at least since the end of World War II, and since heads of state can call each other or take a plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of a few small representation exercises, have turned into espionage centers.
Any viewer of investigative films knows this very well, and it is only by hypocrisy that one pretends to ignore it.
However, publicly repeating it violates the duty of hypocrisy, and serves to put American diplomacy in a bad light.
Secondly, the idea that any hacker can capture the most secretive secrets of the most powerful country in the world is a significant blow to the prestige of the State Department.
Therefore, the scandal does not put the victims as much in crisis as the "boars".
But let’s get to the deep nature of what happened.
In the days of Orwell, all power could be conceived as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
The Orwellian prophecy had been completely proven since, being able to control every movement through the telephone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the highway taken and so on, the citizen became the total victim of the eye of power.
But when it is demonstrated, as it is now, that even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control report ceases to be unidirectional and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker - elected as the avenger of the citizen - can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that no longer has the ability to keep its own secrets hold?
It is true, Georg Simmel already said, that a real secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is true, too, that all knowledge about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is indeed an empty secret, because it is in the public domain; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks did, that Hillary Clinton’s secrets were empty secrets means to take away all power from her.
WikiLeaks has done no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but has made it too big for Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this injury inflicted on a very powerful power?
It is obvious that in the future, states will no longer be able to post any reserved information online - this would be like publishing it on a poster glued around the corner.
But it is just as obvious that with current technologies, it is vain to hope to be able to maintain confidential reports over the phone.
There is nothing easier than to find out if and when a head of state traveled by plane and contacted one of his colleagues.
How can private and reserved reports be maintained in the future?
I know well that, for now, my forecast is science fiction and therefore novel, but I am obliged to imagine government agents who move discreetly in diligences to uncontrollable routes, carrying only messages learned from the heart or, at most, by hiding the rare information written in the heart.
The information will be kept as a single copy in locked drawers: at bottom, the Watergate espionage attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that technology is now advancing in crab, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet re-established a wire telegraph (telephone).
The videotapes (analogue) had allowed the film researchers to explore a film step by step, going forward and backward and discovering all the secrets of the editing, while now the CDs (digital) only allow to jump from chapter to chapter, i.e. by macroportions.
With high-speed trains, we go from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, and the travels that it includes, it takes three and a half hours.
It is therefore not extraordinary that politics and communication techniques are used for horse-drawn cars.
One last observation.
In the past, the press was trying to understand what was going on in the secrets of the embassies.
Now, it is the embassies that ask the press for confidential information.
Climate: How France is hacking its financing promises
One year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to review the fulfilment of the pledges of fast-start or early financing made by developed countries.
And the big French scams are revealed.
In the Copenhagen agreement, developed countries pledged to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has pledged €7.2 billion over three years and France €1.26 billion (420 million per year).
At the opening of COP16, the EU put out the big game to persuade its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast start financing: report detailing the actions of its member states, press conference, big side event, distribution of brochures...
The Transparency operation is appreciable and appreciated at its best: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same with the same level of precision.
The EU announced €2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on track to meet its commitment of €7.2 billion in 2012.
But when you look at the details, things are more complicated.
This money must be, according to the Copenhagen agreement, "new and additional", to ensure that additional effort is made without being to the detriment of Public Development Assistance.
Unfortunately, there is no agreement on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission had proposed harmonization, some Member States whose France blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
For example, the European Commission has considered 2009 as the reference year: international financing is maintained, and it adds 150 million over three years under fast start financing.
Other countries have chosen similar references in terms of year or level of official development assistance.
On the contrary, France considers that the financing of "all new projects" of the year 2010 is "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to expenditures in previous years or to the overall level of Public Development Assistance.
Concretely, the total amount of France’s support to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease), it claims to respect its commitment in terms of “new and additional” financing...
Another crucial element is the distribution between donations and loans.
Again, there is no rule and everyone chooses his or her own way of calculating.
Some, like France, consider that 1€ loaned equals 1€ given.
Obviously, this is hard to justify: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often projects related to emissions mitigation that are based on more efficient technologies), it is wrong to present a euro that will be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is given... At most, should be counted against its commitments only the cost of the loan for the lending country (i.e. the equivalent).
But France has to make such a reasoning: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by making 91.5% loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% donations (36.1 million euros) - see the EU document to verify for yourself.
It is the only country in the Union to use the loan so massively.
Germany requires 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands and Slovakia (in other countries) meet their commitments with 100% of donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union puts €1 to meet its commitment, France puts only 10 cents and considers that the effort is comparable.
Nice pass-through tour!
In short, in its fast-start financing, France operates a double scam: on the one hand on the evolution of action over time and on the other hand on the reality of the financial effort.
By spending only 36.1 million euros, it manages to make it seem that it spends 420 million "new and additional" in accordance with its promises.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that it was Bercy who carried out the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other member states continue to give if it was enough to lend?) and in the negotiations since the developing countries are not completely duped...
The chapter on early financing is only a small, relatively short-term issue in relation to all climate discussions.
But it could be one more grain of sand in the huge machine that is the UNFCCC.
Hopefully this will not be the case.
In any case, it is essential to learn from this first year of early funding.
First of all, France could announce a change in its method of accounting for the years 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its commitments and fairness with the other countries of the European Union.
Above all, France could advance discussions on long-term financing issues (another crucial chapter currently discussed): the question of "additionality" or the method of accounting for loans will not be avoided.
France could change its position to become as progressive on these issues as it is on others.
The hope therefore rests on the new Minister of the Environment, Ms. Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about France's fast start and its vision of "additionality" and the use of loans would increase the level of international confidence needed to move forward in the discussions.
